Some islands still in lockdown. Special restrictions for over 65's and other vulnerable groups. No loitering in public spaces.
People under 25 and over 65 only allowed out for four hours, once a week. Also, some provinces in lockdown.
Three zones for three different alert levels each one defining different movement restrictions.
Curfew for under 18's and over 65 remains only in Republika Srpska.
Stay at home mandatory for vulnerable groups of people.
Self imposed lockdown and curfews in several regions or cities.
Under 18's and over 65 only allowed out in certain days and times.
Weekend only curfew.
Different policies for each territory, with most of them being under lockdown.

Many lockdown style measures. Pm quoted saying "harsher lockdown would be unrealistic given that there are many citizens who don't have homes and even those who have homes have to make ends meet daily".
Borders closed to all foreigners. Lockdown announced by the government but blocked by High Court.
People over 63 can only leave home for pre -defined set of reasons.
People are not allowed to stay in their cabins or other leisure homes.
Moscow self imposes lockdown, and many cities and regions follow the example.
People under 25 and over 65 in complete lockdown nationwide. Also, some provinces in lockdown.
Varied responses among states, with most states imposing lockdown at some point.
People can travel within 500m of their home
Children under 18 cannot leave the house whithout adult supervision.
Children under 13 cannot leave the house whithout adult supervision.
Curfew imposed for 65+ only.
Only one person from each household can leave the house, except for individuals working in permitted industries or seeking medical help.
Only two people from each household can leave the house, except for individuals working in permitted industries or seeking medical help.
Strict lockdown for 7 days, and more relaxed measures including open shops for 7 days on a rolling basis.

Provinces are given power to moderate their restriction measures - so restrictions vary. Some of the stricter measures in the capital include residents only being allowed out of their homes in certain days (depending on their national identity card number) and children not allowed  out at all (will later be allowed out for to socialise for a maximum of 1 hour, in certain days, following social distancing rules and wearing masks).
Some travel restrictions in place. Ongoing conflict prevents a lot of otherwise normal activities like gatherings so excessive measures for COVID-19 probably not needed.
Only two people of each household allowed out for buying necesities at a time in larger cities and intercity travel restricted.
Travelling banned to and from major cities: Marrakech, Fez, Casablanca, Tangier, Mecnes

Stay at home required for red zones.     Outside the red zones, all the government, semi-government, autonomous and non-government offices would remain open in their respective arrangements on a limited scale while no one would be allowed to go out at night from 8:00pm to 6:00am without an emergency during the extended restriction period effective from today.

General Curfew in place from 22:00 to 05:00. Over 80's completely restricted from going out. Lockdown in several parts of the country where people are only allowed out with permits up to two times per week.
General curfew 18:00 - 06:00 on weekdays and 24-hour on weekends.
General curfew 20:00 - 05:00. Under 18's and over 65 not allowed out at all.

General curfew between 20:00 and 06:00. - In non curfew times, a maximum of two households can meet (four adults with a maximum of six children). This also applies to private areas outside the living area (e.g. gardens, barns, sheds, garages).
General curfew 19:00 - 05:00, and children only allowed outside with guardians. Total lockdown over the weekenday (and later just for Sunday). Stricter rules in some areas.
General curfew 20:00 - 06:00, Thursday to Sunday, plus stricter measures on a per Emirate basis.
General curfew imposed, but not due to COVID-19.

Turkish citizens and residents are subject to a weekend curfew (Friday, 9 PM- Monday, 5 AM). Turkish citizens and residents aged 65 and older are restricted to their place of residence, and only allowed outside between 10:00 and 13:00. Turkish citizens and residents aged 20 and below are only allowed outside during the hours of 13:00 and 16:00.
Usual lockdown rules: going out of home is only allowed for certain pre-defined reasons (grocery shopping, helping someone in need, visit to doctor or pharmacy, exercising etc).

Usual lockdown rules: going out of home is only allowed for certain pre-defined reasons (grocery shopping, helping someone in need, visit to doctor or pharmacy, exercising etc). Plus a night time curfew where movement is completely frobidden.
24-hour curfew. Citizens can only go out 2 times per week (based on their surnames) for very basic needs.

Usual lockdown rules: going out of home is only allowed for certain pre-defined reasons (grocery shopping, helping someone in need, visit to doctor or pharmacy, exercising etc). Violators are fined. Additionally, people can only leave home in particular days according to rota, people under 18 and over 65 cannot leave at all.

Usual lockdown rules: going out of home is only allowed for certain pre-defined reasons (grocery shopping, helping someone in need, visit to doctor or pharmacy, exercising etc). Violators are fined. People can only be out dureing a 1.5h window (later changed to 3-hour window, and then to a 4-hour window).

Usual lockdown rules: going out of home is only allowed for certain pre-defined reasons (grocery shopping, helping someone in need, visit to doctor or pharmacy, exercising etc). Violators are fined. Additionally, a total ban in cars, motorcycles, boats etc.
24-hour curfew. Citizens can only go out 1 time per week according to their Id card number. No one allowed out on Weekends.

Usual lockdown rules: going out of home is only allowed for certain pre-defined reasons (grocery shopping, helping someone in need, visit to doctor or pharmacy, exercising etc). Violators are fined. Under 18's cannot go out without adult supervision.

Usual lockdown rules: going out of home is only allowed for certain pre-defined reasons (grocery shopping, helping someone in need, visit to doctor or pharmacy, exercising etc). Violators are fined. Children not allowed outside at all.
All citizens are required to stay at home, and only one member of the family is allowed to leave to do essential shopping.
Lockdown, with residents only allowed out for specified reasons, on on specific days based on the first letter of their surname.
General lockdown with citizens only allowed outside in certain days based on the last digit of their ID numbers.
A 24-hour curfew in place (lockdown) which is lifted every 2-3 days for 8-10 hours.
